# JavaScript / TypeScript Standards

## Style
- Use `const` by default, `let` when reassignment is needed, never `var`
- Arrow functions for callbacks and short functions
- Template literals over string concatenation
- Destructuring for objects and arrays
- Optional chaining (`?.`) and nullish coalescing (`??`)
- Async/await over raw promises; handle errors with try/catch

## Modules
- ES modules (`import`/`export`) preferred over CommonJS
- Named exports preferred over default exports
- Group imports: external libs, then internal modules, then relative paths

## Error Handling
```javascript
// Always catch and handle meaningfully
try {
  const data = await fetchData();
} catch (error) {
  console.error('Failed to fetch data:', error.message);
  throw new AppError('Data fetch failed', { cause: error });
}
```

## React Specifics (when applicable)
- Functional components only
- Custom hooks for reusable logic (prefix with `use`)
- Keep components focused — split large components
- Use Tailwind CSS or CSS Modules for styling
